<script type="application/json" data-for="htmlwidget-7cf30c996e97409e7945">{"x":{"filter":"none","vertical":false,"data":[["All phases, several tasks                                          ","PPI member identification                                          ","PPI member identification                                          ","Priority setting and understanding PPI member perspectives early on","Priority setting and understanding PPI member perspectives early on","Priority setting and understanding PPI member perspectives early on"],["Not HIV-specific, but really good guidance for all phases of lab research is provided here:","Systematic participatory mapping incl. snowball sampling                                   ","Active outreach to recruit PPI members using several strategies                            ","Research agenda setting meeting                                                            ","Research agenda setting meeting                                                            ","One day workshop                                                                           "],["A practical guide to patient and public involvement in lab-based research from NIHR. Including case examples.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            ","A committee of ten people living with HIV (PLHIV) was recruited from community and clinical settings. Sampling sought to include PLHIV with: Different durations of antiretroviral therapy use (three months minimum), varying levels of experience with HIV research or community organizing and abilities to share experiences in a group. We sought representation of different age groups and of the main groups affected by HIV in Quebec, that is: gay, bisexual, and other men who have sex with men (62% of PLHIV in Quebec), people from HIV endemic countries (15%), heterosexual women (10%) and people who inject drugs (4%). Investigators arbitrarily decided that the Team would include a maximum of ten members, all adults, based in Montreal, Canada. To recruit, four Montreal-based community organizations, with which investigators had previously collaborated, and health professionals at the McGill University Health Centre displayed flyers or suggested potential members. Interested individuals (n = 19) contacted the project coordinator by phone. The projectâ€™s main objectives and general expectations (eg, to attend meetings) were then explained.","Several strategies were used to recruit PPI members. We (1) approached several individual PPI members who had participated in the initial focus groups or in the pilot study of the intervention; (2) mailed letters or invitations with information about the study to leaders in the HIV field, Community-based organisations, faith-based organizations, HIV medical care providers, and other service agencies to attend an informational meeting about the project; (3) reviewed an existing database of former advocates and PPI members who served on previous projects and mailed them the invitational letter; and (4) accepted referrals via word of mouth from colleagues and associates.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     ","This study aimed to identify the lived experience research priorities for improving HRQL and identify interventions to support priority areas. A Research Advisory Group was established with 15 lived experience, academic, healthcare, and third sector professionals. Additionally, two semi-structured focus groups were undertaken, with health and third sector professionals and people living with HIV with Cognitive Impairement (focus of the study). Participants were asked to rank factors impacting health-related quality of life, identified in prior research, in terms of priority and intervention development. Findings were analysed using a combination of conventional and summative content analysis.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            ","Plain English Summary review and study rationale discussion (1 session). Consulting with different PPI groups such as Patients in Research website, Terrence Higgins Trust, Family Planning Association, PPI contacts, Pathway Homeless Charity, Community Advisory board to understand the HIV landscape and the potential issues that could arise when implementing HIV testing in dental settings. Guided by 1 PPI member.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            ","A group of five ovarian cancer patients were invited to a one day workshop at a cancer research laboratory.  The workshop involved an initial meet and greet where committee members were introduced to each other and the research team. This was followed by a lab tour and a group discussion, where committee members watched a short presentation about the research project and were then asked specific questions about their treatment experience.  This discussion fed directly into the experimental plans. The decision to include a range of several drugs of a specific class in the experiments, instead of selecting just one, came as a direct result of speaking to patients                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            "